{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0c8380db-dc9c-4b1f-b920-e23d3f1140ae","content":"You're on **MSTest v3.8.2** targeting `net9.0`. Here's the modern approach:\n\n### Constructor injection for `TestContext` + sync init\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private readonly MyService _service;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Asynchronous initialization here\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points (MSTest v3):**\n- **`TestContext`** is injected via the **constructor** — no need for a settable property.\n- Use the **constructor** for synchronous setup (runs before each test).\n- Use **`[TestInitialize]`** with `async Task` for async setup.\n- For one-time class-level async init, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static, takes `TestContext` parameter).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13ab17d9-bd22-43c9-8a37-6db0564e2a06","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2. Let me provide guidance on the modern way to do test initialization in MSTest v3.\n\nIn MSTest v3:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest v3, `TestContext` can be injected via a constructor parameter. The old way was to use a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property, but the modern way is constructor injection.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[ClassInitialize]` (static) and `[TestInitialize]` (instance) methods for synchronous init. But `[TestInitialize]` can also be async.\n\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Both `[ClassInitialize]` and `[TestInitialize]` support async variants using `async Task` return types for per-test and class-level setup respectively. The `TestContext` gets passed as a parameter to `[ClassInitialize]`, while `[TestInitialize]` is an instance method that runs before each test.\n\nFor synchronous setup, I can use the constructor directly, but async initialization requires the `[TestInitialize]` attribute with an async method.","outputTokens":670,"requestId":"1041:1B7339:36CC591:3C96115:6A02ED06"},"id":"1a88478f-e6f2-4b87-8a56-a67d81cd72a0","timestamp":"2026-05-12T09:04:19.918Z","parentId":"e4172176-410a-48eb-a860-7c95f2489081"}
